    <h1>Central Limit Theorem</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Grinstead &amp; Snell &middot; GFDL &middot; <a href="https://math.dartmouth.edu/~prob/prob/prob.pdf">PDF</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Standardize the sum of <em>n</em> independent random variables: subtract the mean, divide by &sigma;&radic;n. As <em>n</em> grows, the distribution converges to N(0, 1). This is why the normal distribution appears everywhere.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. The standardized sum -->
    <h3>The standardized sum</h3>
    <p>Let X&#x2081;, X&#x2082;, &hellip;, X&#x2099; be independent random variables with mean &mu; and variance &sigma;&sup2;. Their sum S&#x2099; = X&#x2081; + &hellip; + X&#x2099; has mean n&mu; and variance n&sigma;&sup2;. The <strong>standardized sum</strong> is S&#x2099;* = (S&#x2099; &minus; n&mu;) / (&sigma;&radic;n). The CLT says the distribution of S&#x2099;* converges to the standard normal.</p>

